    <span class="post-date">Jun 28th 2026</span>
  </div>
  <div class="post-body">
    <p>
      <span class="post-opener"
        >Fell down a sleep rabbit hole and found this: your sharpest hours
        aren't a habit, they came preinstalled at birth.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      Your chronotype is mostly genetic, down to a gene called PER3, and it
      quietly schedules when your brain dumps melatonin, cortisol,
      adrenaline, and dopamine. Know your type and you stop fighting the clock,
      you just line the day up with it, when to work hard, when to have coffee,
      when not to.
    </p>
    <p>There are four animals:</p>
    <p>
      <strong>&#129409; Lion (10-15%)</strong> &mdash; the early bird. Awake by
      5 or 6, peaks for real work around 9:30 to 11:30, and basically clocks out
      by 8:30pm.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>&#128059; Bear (50-55%)</strong> &mdash; most of us. The whole
      9-to-5 world was built for them. Best stretch is roughly noon to 2pm.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>&#128058; Wolf (15-20%)</strong> &mdash; the night owl. Creative,
      hates mornings, brain lights up at 2am, and the biggest risk-taker of the
      bunch.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>&#128044; Dolphin (10%)</strong> &mdash; light sleeper, smart,
      anxious, obsessed with detail, desperate for sleep but never quite gets
      enough. This one was named by a Dr. Breus.
    </p>
    <hr class="post-divider" />
    <p>
      And it's not fixed for life. One starts as a Lion baby, becomes a Bear
      kid, then a Wolf teen, settles into a single type as an adult, and shifts
      earlier again in their 50s.
    </p>
    <p>
      No idea which one I am yet, but it would explain why every attempt at
      becoming an early bird has quietly died.
    </p>
